(1, '2014-05-08', '2014-05-13', 'John Smith', 'news', 'Audi unveils updated 3.0-litre V6 diesel engine', 'Ready to take on increasingly strict European emissions standards, Audi has unveiled a pair of revised 3.0-litre diesel V6 engines.', '', 'Revealed at the Vienna Auto Symposium in Austria earlier today, the new engines benefit from components revised in the bid to reduce friction. To name just a few of the extensive changes, the new diesel V6 benefits from redesigned cylinder heads, new piston rings and a revised turbocharger.\r\n\r\nNot only do the revisions translate to a 13 per cent improvement in fuel economy in certain models, but horsepower and torque figures are also up. Audi says the engine offers up to 272 horsepower and 442 lb.-ft. of torque, again in certain models.\r\n\r\nThe changes come just one year following the introduction of Audi’s current crop of diesel V6 engines in North America. Available in the A6, A7, A8 and Q5 models, the outgoing diesel V6 pumps out 240 horsepower and 428 lb.-ft. of torque.', 'Cars, Audi, Engine, V6, Diesel, 3.0 litre', 'audi_unveils_updated_3litre_V6_diesel_engine'),
(3, '2014-05-08', '2014-05-13', 'Jane Doe', 'reviews', 'German sports car manufacturer Wiesmann shuts down', 'Wiesmann has shut its doors for good after years of manufacturing bespoke, BMW-powered sports cars.', '', 'Wiesmann has shut its doors for good after years of manufacturing bespoke, BMW-powered sports cars.\r\n\r\nThe company first encountered financial issues in 2009 when a planned expansion fell at the same time as the global recession of that year. Ultimately, Wiesmann filed for bankruptcy protection last year, and despite coming up with a plan to save the brand and its 125 employees, AutoExpress says a buyer for the company after it kept on incurring debt.\r\n\r\nWiesmann started out in 1985 as a firm that manufactured hard-top roofs for convertibles. A few years later, it expanded into building bespoke sports cars with retro styling and powertrains derived from BMW’s M division. Currently, Wiesmann’s most powerful model is the GT MF5, a fiberglass-bodied coupe powered by a twin-turbocharged V8 engine from the BMW X5 M.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Wiesmann has shut its doors for good after years of manufacturing \r\nbespoke, BMW-powered sports cars.\r\n\r\nThe company first encountered financial issues in 2009 when a planned \r\nexpansion fell at the same time as the global recession of that year. \r\nUltimately, Wiesmann filed for bankruptcy protection last year, and \r\ndespite coming up with a plan to save the brand and its 125 employees, \r\nAutoExpress says a buyer for the company after it kept on incurring \r\ndebt.\r\n\r\nWiesmann started out in 1985 as a firm that manufactured hard-top roofs \r\nfor convertibles. A few years later, it expanded into building bespoke \r\nsports cars with retro styling and powertrains derived from BMW’s M \r\ndivision. Currently, Wiesmann’s most powerful model is the GT MF5, a \r\nfiberglass-bodied coupe powered by a twin-turbocharged V8 engine from \r\nthe BMW X5 M.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Wiesmann has shut its doors for good after years of manufacturing \r\nbespoke, BMW-powered sports cars.\r\n\r\nThe company first encountered financial issues in 2009 when a planned \r\nexpansion fell at the same time as the global recession of that year. \r\nUltimately, Wiesmann filed for bankruptcy protection last year, and \r\ndespite coming up with a plan to save the brand and its 125 employees, \r\nAutoExpress says a buyer for the company after it kept on incurring \r\ndebt.\r\n\r\nWiesmann started out in 1985 as a firm that manufactured hard-top roofs \r\nfor convertibles. A few years later, it expanded into building bespoke \r\nsports cars with retro styling and powertrains derived from BMW’s M \r\ndivision. Currently, Wiesmann’s most powerful model is the GT MF5, a \r\nfiberglass-bodied coupe powered by a twin-turbocharged V8 engine from \r\nthe BMW X5 M.', 'Wiesmann, German, Sports Car, Manufacturers', 'german_sports_car_manufacturer_Wiesmann_shuts_down'),
(5, '2014-05-08', '2014-05-13', 'Adam Smith', 'news', 'Eight useless and funky pickups you secretly want', 'Pickups are known for their practicality, but if you think they''re too big, here''s a handful of oddball alternatives', '', 'Pickups most often come in one size: Big. It makes many people happy, but eventually, you’re going to get that one person who inevitably wants the practicality of a pickup but in a smaller package.\r\n\r\nSure, it’s a novel concept at first, but it rarely works because practicality is usually compromised due to their smaller size. Then there’s the aesthetic factor — a car with its rear end lopped off and replaced with a bed looks downright frumpy. Yet somehow, as automakers experiment with car-based pickups, frumpy turns into funky because some of these creations over the years actually look hilarious … both in good and bad ways. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Here’s a handful of some of our favourites:\r\n\r\nBMW M3 Pickup\r\nThe BMW M3 Pickup\r\n\r\nThe BMW M3 Pickup\r\nHandout, BMW\r\n\r\nIn the weeks leading up to April Fools’ Day three years ago, BMW was “testing” a new variant of the now previous-generation M3 family on the Nurburgring. As it turns out, it was a prank, but a good one nonetheless because the M3 Pickup created such a buzz. Powered by the standard M3?s V8 engine, it pumps out 420 horsepower and is surprisingly only 110 pounds heavier than the M3 convertible. It features a reasonably sized bed out back, as well as a targa roof because open-air motoring is a must. Although you would think BMW would rush to putting it into production given its knack for niche vehicles, the M3 Pickup is a one-off model used as a workshop vehicle to ferry around parts for the M division.\r\n\r\nChevrolet El Camino\r\nThe Chevrolet El Camino\r\n\r\nThe Chevrolet El Camino\r\nHandout, GM\r\n\r\nThis is the car-based pickup that arguably started it all back in 1959. Based on the Chevrolet Brookwoods wagon, the El Camino was basically GM’s answer to the Ford Ranchero. It was something of a hit in 1959, but its popularity faded a year later and was discontinued. But in 1964, GM gave the El Camino a new lease on life and a new platform along with it. It was now based on the Chevrolet Chevelle, and that meant it also shared its engines.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;That’s actually a good thing, particularly in 1970 because that is when GM stuffed the Chevelle’s massive LS5 454 cubic-inch V8 under the hood of certain El Caminos, giving it 425 horsepower, 460 lb.-ft. of torque. Quarter-mile times ruled back in the age of the muscle car, and the 454-equipped El Camino could do it in about 13 seconds. Even by today’s standards, that’s pretty impressive.\r\n\r\nChevrolet SSR\r\nThe Chevrolet SSR\r\n\r\nThe Chevrolet SSR\r\nHandout, GM\r\n\r\nAs a concept car at the 2000 North American International Auto Show, the outlandish Chevrolet SSR was acceptable. After all, concepts are for dreaming, right? Well, three years later and for some odd reason, GM decided to build the SSR. It certainly had the performance chops, at least on paper — it was powered by GM’s 5.3-litre Vortec V8 engine pumping out 300 horsepower. Unfortunately, it was initially paired to a four-speed automatic transmission, which neutered performance to say the least. Nothing could save the SSR — be it the retro styling or the Corvette-derived LS2 V8 and six-speed manual added in 2005 — from the chopping block.\r\n\r\nFord Falcon and Holden Commodore Ute\r\nThe HSV Maloo R8\r\n\r\nThe HSV Maloo R8\r\nHandout, GM\r\n\r\nShort for “utility,” utes are an interesting niche of the automotive industry. Again, similar in concept to the El Camino, utes are especially popular in Australia for their driving dynamics, looks (hey, beauty is subjective…) and practicality. At least we can get behind the performance part: Holden, for instance, offers the HSV Maloo R8, based on the Commodore and complete with a 6.2-litre, 425-horsepower V8 under the hood. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Talk about hauling!\r\n\r\nMini Paceman Adventure\r\nThe Mini Paceman Adventure\r\n\r\nThe Mini Paceman Adventure\r\nHandout, BMW\r\n\r\nNow we’re beginning to think BMW has a secret affinity for car-based pickups. Developed by a team of interns at the automaker’s Munich and Dingolfing plants, the Mini Paceman Adventure is considerably more awesome than its chubby, fixed-roof coupe variant. Under the skin, the Paceman Adventure is powered by a 184-horsepower turbo-four, fed to all four wheels via a six-speed manual. But that’s not all: there’s a bunch of features that make it surprisingly badass, including a beefed-up suspension, a snorkel and some very bright spotlights. And like the M3 Pickup, the Paceman Adventure is road legal, but that doesn’t mean it’s going into production.\r\n\r\nPeugeot 207 Hoggar\r\nThe Peugeot 207 Hoggar\r\n\r\nThe Peugeot 207 Hoggar\r\nHandout, Peugeot\r\n\r\nOriginally, the Peugeot Hoggar was basically a really cool dune buggy with a one-piece carbon honeycomb body, four-wheel-drive and two diesel engines. Unfortunately, none of that awesomeness seems to have transferred into the production version, which has been available in South America since 2010.\r\n\r\nSubaru BRAT/Baja\r\nThe Subaru Baja\r\n\r\nThe Subaru Baja\r\nHandout, Subaru\r\n\r\nUntil recently, Subaru has strayed from the mainstream by focusing on often oddball vehicles. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Among them is the Subaru Bi-drive Recreational All-terrain Transporter, or BRAT for short. Introduced in 1978, the BRAT’s most distinguishing feature was the rear-facing jumpseats in the bed, which didn’t do much in the way of practicality. Then, in 2003, Subaru followed up on the BRAT’s formula with the Baja, an equally offbeat “pickup” based on the Legacy that, once again, wasn’t all that practical. It wasn’t that pretty, either.\r\n\r\nSuzuki Mighty Boy\r\nThe Suzuki Mighty Boy\r\n\r\nThe Suzuki Mighty Boy\r\nSupplied, Wikimedia Commons\r\n\r\nThe grass is almost always greener on the other side, which probably explains why those itty-bitty subcompact “Kei” cars are so popular in Japan. There are plenty of variants tooting around, including hatchbacks, baby convertibles, and evidently pickups. It’s probably the only 550-cc pickup, and despite its underpinnings shared with the Suzuki Cervo, the Mighty Boy was classified as a commercial vehicle. These cute little things evidently still have a dedicated following in Japan, probably because it easily wins over your heart with its pint-sized everything despite them being not exactly practical, what with a bed measuring 600 millimetres long and all that.', 'Pickup, Suzuki, BMW M3', 'eight_useless_and_funky_pickups_you_secretly_want'),
(6, '2014-05-08', '2014-05-13', 'John Doe', 'news', 'Porsche envisions more hybrids and horsepower by 2017', 'Porsche has spilled the beans on its plans for the next three years, consisting of two main components: lots of horsepower, and lots of hybrids.', '', 'According to a report from Motor Trend, we can expect plug-in hybrid technology from the 918 Spyder to trickle down into the 911 Turbo S and Panamera Turbo S, translating to a horsepower boost into the neighbourhood of 700 horsepower. In addition, the Cayenne Turbo S is also expected to see a similar hybrid option. All three vehicles will be tagged with the e-Hybrid badge, like the 918 Spyder, though it’s unclear if those models will outright replace the Turbo S versions as the flagship performance models.\r\n\r\nAs for the Cayenne, we already told you about the “coupe” variant in the pipeline. Porsche is still on track to launch it as the Cayenne Sport Turismo, offered initially in e-Hybrid form and with less powerful (and less expensive) variants to follow.\r\n\r\nA Sport Turismo version is also in the cards for the Panamera, which is expected to account for 20 per cent of total sales. If it sees the light of day, the Panamera Sport Turismo will be pegged as a competitor to the likes of the Audi A7, BMW 6 Series Gran Coupe and the Mercedes-Benz CLS. In addition, Porsche is also expected to shoehorn a plug-in hybrid powertrain into the Panamera S.\r\n\r\nIf the news of hybrids has you throwing your arms up in protest thus far, fret not because the final piece of the Porsche puzzle is arguably the most enticing. Because the Boxster and Cayman GTS aren’t enough, Porsche is planning even more extreme versions of each car. Badged as the Cayman GT4, it will be something of a baby 911 GT3, complete with a modified PDK gearbox and will carry a price tag of about US$125,000.\r\n\r\nThe powertrain, however, is still up in the air: If Porsche sees success with the 919 Hybrid at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, expect a turbocharged four-cylinder engine mounted in the middle with an electric assist, much like the race car. If not, the company’s trademark flat-six is also a possibility. We can also expect a GT4 version of the Boxster, likely badged as the RS Spyder.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;According to a report from Motor Trend, we can expect plug-in hybrid \r\ntechnology from the 918 Spyder to trickle down into the 911 Turbo S and \r\nPanamera Turbo S, translating to a horsepower boost into the \r\nneighbourhood of 700 horsepower. In addition, the Cayenne Turbo S is \r\nalso expected to see a similar hybrid option. All three vehicles will be\r\n tagged with the e-Hybrid badge, like the 918 Spyder, though it’s \r\nunclear if those models will outright replace the Turbo S versions as \r\nthe flagship performance models.\r\n\r\nAs for the Cayenne, we already told you about the “coupe” variant in the\r\n pipeline. Porsche is still on track to launch it as the Cayenne Sport \r\nTurismo, offered initially in e-Hybrid form and with less powerful (and \r\nless expensive) variants to follow.\r\n\r\nA Sport Turismo version is also in the cards for the Panamera, which is \r\nexpected to account for 20 per cent of total sales. If it sees the light\r\n of day, the Panamera Sport Turismo will be pegged as a competitor to \r\nthe likes of the Audi A7, BMW 6 Series Gran Coupe and the Mercedes-Benz \r\nCLS. In addition, Porsche is also expected to shoehorn a plug-in hybrid \r\npowertrain into the Panamera S.\r\n\r\nIf the news of hybrids has you throwing your arms up in protest thus \r\nfar, fret not because the final piece of the Porsche puzzle is arguably \r\nthe most enticing. Because the Boxster and Cayman GTS aren’t enough, \r\nPorsche is planning even more extreme versions of each car. Badged as \r\nthe Cayman GT4, it will be something of a baby 911 GT3, complete with a \r\nmodified PDK gearbox and will carry a price tag of about US$125,000.\r\n\r\nThe powertrain, however, is still up in the air: If